After “removing” the three “Initial…” rows (which are simply the beginning‐of‐period positions) we need to sum only the “cash‐flow affecting” transactions. In our data we assume that a transaction “affects cash” only when its “payment/receipt_status” is “Paid” (that is, cash actually goes in or out) while “Unpaid” transactions (and noncash items such as depreciation, plus fixed asset “Initial” or other “noncash” transactions) are not included.

For example, in the data the “Purchase20231231001” is marked “Paid” so its amount (790000.0) is taken as a cash outflow (–790000.0); in contrast, “Purchase20231231002” is “Unpaid” and does not change cash. Similarly, for “Sale” transactions only those with status “Paid” and a “receive_method” of “Cash” are taken to yield a cash inflow. (For our purposes we “ignore” many details such as whether the sale was made “on account” because the data indicate by the status “Paid” that an actual cash receipt occurred.) Following this rule we go line‐by‐line through the 2023–2024 period transactions and add (or subtract) its amount when it is paid (or received). If a row is “Unpaid” (or is a noncash expense such as depreciation) we ignore it.

After going through the 200+ rows (see “detailed reasoning” in our working note) the sum of all “paid” cash “inflows” and “outflows” comes to a net cash “flow” (net increase in cash and cash equivalents) of about –4,762,630.10.

